From that moment, every time my sis @fraferragni and I would take a flight we would spend all the time looking out of the windows, trying to spot my grandma waving at us from the clouds.
Even now, 25 years later, I always ask for a window seat to say hello to my grandma in the clouds. She‚Äôs my guardian angel

In these past months I tried to get more in deep conversations with people I care about. My husband, my friends, my family, but sometimes even friends of friends that I met at a dinner. I‚Äôm obsessed about everyone‚Äôs idea of a life pursuit, and what life real meaning could be for each of us. And, in one of these deep conversations about life and happiness, one person, whose thoughts I really admire, made me think about this: have you ever noticed that, most of the times, the memories you have of a particular good moment in your life become more enjoyable in your mind than the moment itself? This happens because we‚Äôre not fully present in the moment. A part of us is thinking about something else, we might be browsing our phone, or listening to others‚Äô conversations. It happens to me all the time: I have the best memories of trips, special moments and awesome people I shared them with, but in those moments.. Well I couldn‚Äôt understand 100% how precious they were. Maybe only 80%. So this is my goal for this year, and for my life in general: being more present. Enjoying the beauty of a sunset, a laugh, a warm hug without thinking about anything else. But for real. Think about it too üíò

Looking back at February and March 2018 photos and my heart melts. When you were inside me, little Leo, I felt like we were one whole thing. You could travel with me everywhere, eat everything I was eating, kick me when you wanted to make me feel ‚ÄúI‚Äôm here mum‚Äù. You made me feel magical, powerful and strong. But I was always also wondering ‚Äúwill I be a good mum to you, little Edamame? (we used to call you like that when you were as small as an edamame and we didn‚Äôt know your gender ‚ò∫Ô∏è) And then I thought about how much love I could give you, and I felt safe. I‚Äôll make tons of mistakes as a parent, but I‚Äôll always make sure you‚Äôll be loved and you‚Äôll feel special. This is my promise to you. Because I love you like my heart could explode not only when I see you, but everytime I think about you ‚ù§Ô∏è

This was me, exactly a year ago. I was 36 weeks pregnant, at home rest in Los Angeles, with Mati and Fede by my side, ready to meet my baby boy. At that time I remember I decided not to post this photo, and It was not because I had a stain on my white denim. I felt insecure about sharing my body at that stage of the pregnancy. I am not always self confident, and even If i have a great relationship with my body most of the time, a pregnancy is both magical and difficult on so many levels. Only women who have tried it can really relate. Now, a year later, holding my favorite person in the world in my arms I can say this: body, I‚Äôm so proud of you. For all the times you made my heart beat, for all the times you loved me back, even when I didn‚Äôt love you enough. For recovering each time and making me experience life, day after day. For waking up, every morning. But, most of all, for creating life. Loving your body is a long process, but I really encourage each one of you to say something nice to yourself, everytime you look at the mirror. This is how the self confidence revolution starts. Love yourself first, so that others will love you too üôèüèª

2014/2015/2016: the revolutionary years. Those were the years I was living full time in Los Angeles (but traveling a lot for work) and started to make it big internationally. 2015 was the year of my first Vogue cover, my Harvard business case study and my Forbes nomination. I was sometimes too skinny, my hair was my natural colour but, despite my career really taking off, I was not 100% happy and was feeling very lonely in LA. In June 2016, after a breakup, I changed my hair color and started getting more in shape. I also started to spend more time back in Italy and, in September 2016, I met the love of my life. You know the rest of the story ü•∞
The face I make when they tell me that daddy‚Äôs #ParanoiaAirlines is PLATINUM RECORD in 1 week üíø Bravissimo amore, so proud of you @fedez ü•∞
Leo as an egg ü§£ This should break any record ahahahha

2011/2012/2013: the in-between years. Those were the times when nobody could still understand what I was doing but, day by day, I was more sure of my path. Haters were always there, but those were the years where I started to really not care, showing a completely different attitude towards those who couldn‚Äôt get me. I started wearing real makeup and get my hair done, and feeling a bit like a woman and not a child anymore. 2012 was the year when I started posting not only on my blog @theblondesalad but also on Instagram, changing my way to communicate with my followers forever. 2013 was the year in which I moved to Los Angeles and my style also became a bit more effortless. #10yearchallenge This was me in 2009, the year that changed my life forever. I was 21, studying international law at Bocconi university, living in a 40 square metre studio apartment in Moscova and working part time as a model. I was investing all my money in designer bags and travels and dreaming to find my way into the world and becoming someone inspiring. I had a thing for Balenciaga bags and eyeliner.
I was already posting my life on the Internet, especially on Flickr, and was already facing trolls and haters trying to put me down. Then, in October 2009, I decided to buy my first real camera (see picture n.9), start my own blog, @theblondesalad and, step by step my whole life changed.
To the young 21 year old Chiara of 2009 I would wanna say this: It‚Äôs ok to not having it all figured out and understand your life little by little, It‚Äôs ok to not feel good 100% of the times and It‚Äôs very wise to enjoy the dark moments too because they‚Äôre part of the process. Enjoy the journey to whatever you‚Äôre doing younger Chiara, and always keep in mind that If you follow your heart, you‚Äôll never make mistakes. And to all the people that will tell you ‚ÄúNobody‚Äôs gonna remember your name in 6 months‚Äù in these years.. Oh well, in 2019 you‚Äôll be able to smile back at them and tell them they were fucking wrong ‚úåüèª
